<DOC><DOCNO> AP890201-0248 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-01-89 0115EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     02-01 0811</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0846</SECOND><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said six taskforces have been created in major cities to combat ``crime in thesuites'' by fighting against securities and commodities fraud.   The attorney general, flanked by U.S. attorneys from New York,Chicago and Kansas City, announced the creation Tuesday of sixsecurities and commodities fraud units in those cities as well as inLos Angeles, Denver, and San Francisco.   The announcement came just weeks after disclosure that federalinvestigators in Chicago had conducted a two-year undercoveroperation that turned up widespread evidence of fraud by commoditiesfutures traders at the Chicago Board of Trade and the ChicagoMercantile Exchange.</TEXT><DATELINE>TRENTON, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   State gaming officials moved to bar DrexelBurnham Lambert Inc. at least temporarily from its lucrativebusiness with New Jersey's casino industry because of the firm'sinvolvement in the Wall Street insider trading scandal.   Anthony J. Parrillo, director of the New Jersey Division ofGaming Enforcement, said Tuesday officials asked the Casino ControlCommission to suspend the investment firm pending a decision onDrexel's application for a license to do business with the AtlanticCity casinos.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A former junior securities analyst convicted ofinsider trading in a major fraud scandal will pay back more than$127,000 in illegal profits under an agreement approved by a federaljudge.   U.S. District Judge Richard Owen approved a final settlementTuesday in which Stephen Wang, without admitting or denyingwrongdoing, agreed to pay $127,585 to satisfy claims arising fromhis role in what the government has called one of the biggest insidetrading frauds in history.</TEXT><DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   France's stock market watchdog agency recommended acriminal investigation of the insider trading scandal that hasembarrassed the Socialist government, but said it could not identifyindividuals guilty of leaking information that led to suspiciousstock purchases.   The Commission des Operations de Bourse said Tuesday Max Theret,a businessman with close ties to the governing Socialist Party, made``eminently suspicious'' purchases of stock in the U.S. companyTriangle Industries Inc. just before it was acquired by the Frenchstate-owned firm Pechiney SA.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Treasury Secretary Nicholas Brady gave aqualified endorsement to limiting tax deductions for interestpayments on debt incurred in leveraged corporate buyouts, if theresulting revenue were used to reduce taxes on stock dividends.   ``If you're going to make a change _ and clearly we're notsuggesting one _ we would suggest that you look in the area ofperhaps limiting interest deductions and using that money to give abreak to corporate owners of stock,'' Brady told the House Ways andMeans Committee on Tuesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prices farmers get for raw products began 1989with a 1.4 percent increase from December to January and were up 12percent from a year ago, the Agriculture Department said.   The department's Agricultural Statistics Board said Tuesday inits first price report of the year that higher prices for cattle,hogs, tomatoes and wheat were partly offset by lower prices forstrawberries, grapefruit, peanuts and oranges.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Foreign investment in the United States helps theeconomy, creates jobs and increases U.S. productive capacity, amajority of corporate leaders said in a survey.   But one in five of those responding said the current accelerationin foreign investment threatens U.S. social and culturalfoundations, said the survey released Tuesday by the accounting andconsulting firm Touche Ross andamp; Co.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The price of Houghton Mifflin Co. stock soaredafter a group led by wealthy Texan Robert M. Bass disclosed itrecently increased its stake in the publisher to 5.6 percent.   The Bass Group said in disclosing its holdings its latestpurchase was for investment purposes, and the company pointed outthat Bass had been an investor in Houghton Mifflin for some time.   Nonetheless, Houghton Mifflin shot up $8.87{ a share to $45.25 intrading Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange.</TEXT><DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Eastern Airlines rejected binding arbitration in the16-month-old contract dispute with its largest union, setting thestage for a 30-day deadline in management's showdown with theMachinists.   Tom Matthews, Eastern senior vice president for human resourcesand chief negotiator, wrote the National Mediation Board on Tuesdaythat Eastern had too much at stake to entrust the decision to athird party.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market finished higher Tuesday, rebounding briskly latein the trading session to lift the Dow Jones average of 30industrials 18.21 points to 2,342.32, its highest close since theOctober 1987 market crash.   The dollar surged to three-month highs.   Bond prices barely budged in light trading.   Grain and soybean futures prices rose sharply and livestock andmeat futures were mostly higher, while precious metal and energyfutures fell.</TEXT></DOC>